For a variety of reasons, local ownership is critical to solving climate change. For starters, local ownership enables more effective decision-making and implementation of climate change mitigation and adaptation strategies. Decisions taken at the local level are more likely to be customized to the community's unique needs and resources rather than being forced from on high. This guarantees that the actions are more successful in addressing the community's particular concerns and are more likely to be accepted and maintained. Second, local ownership encourages community participation and empowerment. Local communities are more likely to be invested in the result and involved in the process when they take ownership of climate change projects. This may result in more community buy-in and support for the initiatives, as well as a feeling of ownership and pride in the city's efforts to combat climate change. Third, local ownership may result in more equal benefit and cost distribution. Local communities that participate in decision-making are more likely to guarantee that the benefits of climate change programs are distributed evenly among all members of the community rather than concentrated in the hands of a few. Finally, local ownership is critical for tackling climate change because it enables more effective decision-making, community involvement and empowerment, and fair sharing of benefits and costs. We can guarantee that climate change mitigation and adaptation strategies are customized to the individual requirements of each community and are more likely to be accepted and maintained by giving local populations a role in the process. 